pursuits, creating a state of moral chaos apparent in the breakdown of relationships in the family, nation, and global Islamic community. Tablighis insist that this dire situation can only be remedied by drawing Muslims back to Islam through dawat, which they regard as the sacred means for spreading Islamic virtue. In a country founded in the name of Muslim identity and where Islam is ubiquitous in public life, the Tablighi claim that Pakistani Muslims have abandoned Islam is particularly striking. The Promise of Piety shows how Tablighis constitute a distinct form of pious relationality in the ritual processes and everyday practices of dawat and how pious relationality serves as a basis for transforming domestic and public life. Khan explores both the promise and limits of the Tablighi project of creating an Islamic moral order that can transcend the political fragmentation and violence of life in postcolonial Pakistan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslam and politicszPakistan. 0aIslamic ethicszPakistan. 0aMuslim menzPakistanxConduct of life. 0aPiety. 4aAsian Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aIslamic piety movement, Tablighis, liberal-secular approaches, Islamic tradition, Pakistani Muslim, identity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501773556?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501773556423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501773556/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles